### ============================================================================
### service-policy — EVALUATION endpoints in detail
###   POST /v1/evaluate        single request  → Decision
###   POST /v1/evaluate/batch  batch requests  → { decisions: [Decision, …] }
###   GET  /v1/permissions      subject + ?app  → cacheable flat permission list
###
### Companion to lifecycle-walkthrough.http. Assumes an ACTIVE policy exists (run
### steps 1–7 of the lifecycle file first).
###
### ⚠️ `app` IS REQUIRED on every evaluation request (ADR-024). Evaluation is scoped
###    by (app, resourceType): a policy of one app can NEVER decide a request of
###    another. Missing app → 400 BAD_REQUEST (on /evaluate AND on every batch item).
###
### Auth: {{jwt}} = any valid authenticated token. Subject is resolved from the JWT
### (ADR-013). An explicit "subject" in the body → delegated query (needs the
### delegation marker, else 403).
### ============================================================================

@host = http://localhost:8080
@auth = Bearer {{jwt}}


### ============================================================================
### A) POST /v1/evaluate  — single authorization request → Decision
### ============================================================================
### REQUEST BODY (EvaluationRequest):
###   app               (REQUIRED)  the application the PEP acts for (ADR-024)
###   action            (required)  "resource:verb", e.g. "document:read"
###   resource          (required)  { type (required), id, attributes: {…} }
###   context           (optional)  runtime attributes, e.g. {"emergency": true}
###   subjectAttributes (optional)  non-identity subject attrs, e.g. {"area": "A"}
###   subject           (optional)  explicit subject → delegated query (ADR-013)
###
### RESPONSE (Decision), HTTP 200 for a valid request:
###   { allowed, reason, decisionId, policyVersion, obligations: [] }
### 400 if app, action or resource.type is blank. Never 500 on operand type (ADR-023).

### A1) PERMIT — subject is an assignee
POST {{host}}/v1/evaluate
Authorization: {{auth}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "app": "rh",
  "action": "document:read",
  "resource": { "type": "document", "id": "d1", "attributes": { "assignees": ["test-user"] } }
}

### EXPECTED  200 OK
### {
###   "allowed": true,
###   "reason": "…assigned-access…",
###   "decisionId": "3f0c…-uuid",
###   "policyVersion": "2",
###   "obligations": []
### }


### A2) PERMIT — with subjectAttributes (area-scope rule)
POST {{host}}/v1/evaluate
Authorization: {{auth}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "app": "rh",
  "action": "document:read",
  "resource": { "type": "document", "id": "d2", "attributes": { "area": "A" } },
  "subjectAttributes": { "area": "A" }
}

### EXPECTED  200 OK  →  allowed: true


### A3) DENY — default deny (nothing matches)
POST {{host}}/v1/evaluate
Authorization: {{auth}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "app": "rh",
  "action": "document:read",
  "resource": { "type": "document", "id": "d4", "attributes": { "assignees": ["someone-else"], "area": "B" } },
  "subjectAttributes": { "area": "A" }
}

### EXPECTED  200 OK  →  allowed: false, policyVersion: "2"


### A4) ISOLATION (ADR-024) — same request, different app → DENY
### The rh policy is invisible to app "nami". Only nami's own policies apply.
POST {{host}}/v1/evaluate
Authorization: {{auth}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "app": "nami",
  "action": "document:read",
  "resource": { "type": "document", "id": "d1", "attributes": { "assignees": ["test-user"] } }
}

### EXPECTED  200 OK  →  allowed: FALSE
### A policy of one app can never decide a request of another. No wildcard, no global.


### A5) DELEGATED query — explicit "subject" (caller needs the delegation marker)
POST {{host}}/v1/evaluate
Authorization: {{auth}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "app": "rh",
  "action": "document:read",
  "resource": { "type": "document", "id": "d5" },
  "subject": "user-x"
}

### EXPECTED  200 OK if the caller carries the delegation marker (decision for user-x)
###           403 FORBIDDEN (problem+json) if it does not (ADR-013)


### A6) 400 — missing `app` (ADR-024: required)
POST {{host}}/v1/evaluate
Authorization: {{auth}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "action": "document:read",
  "resource": { "type": "document", "id": "d1" }
}

### EXPECTED  400  code: "BAD_REQUEST"  →  "app must not be blank."


### A7) 400 — resource.type blank
POST {{host}}/v1/evaluate
Authorization: {{auth}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "app": "rh",
  "action": "document:read",
  "resource": { "id": "d1" }
}

### EXPECTED  400  →  "resource.type must not be blank."


### A8) DENY (not 500) — runtime type mismatch on an ordering operator (ADR-023)
### If the active policy has e.g.  GT subject.attr.clearance vs 5,  and clearance
### arrives as a non-number, the comparison does NOT hold → deny. Never a 500.
POST {{host}}/v1/evaluate
Authorization: {{auth}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "app": "rh",
  "action": "document:read",
  "resource": { "type": "document", "id": "d6" },
  "subjectAttributes": { "clearance": "high" }
}

### EXPECTED  200 OK  →  allowed: false   (incomparable operand → condition false)


### ============================================================================
### B) POST /v1/evaluate/batch  — batch → { decisions: [Decision, …] }
### ============================================================================
### REQUEST BODY (BatchEvaluationRequest):  { "requests": [ EvaluationRequest, … ] }
### RESPONSE (BatchEvaluationResult):        { "decisions": [ Decision, … ] }
###   Results are in the SAME ORDER as the input requests.
###   ⚠️ EVERY item needs `app` (ADR-024). An item without it fails the WHOLE batch
###      with 400 — it does NOT return a silent deny.
###   A delegation violation on ANY item fails the whole batch with 403.

### B1) Batch — three decisions at once
POST {{host}}/v1/evaluate/batch
Authorization: {{auth}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "requests": [
    { "app": "rh", "action": "document:read",
      "resource": { "type": "document", "id": "d1", "attributes": { "assignees": ["test-user"] } } },
    { "app": "rh", "action": "document:read",
      "resource": { "type": "document", "id": "d4", "attributes": { "area": "B" } },
      "subjectAttributes": { "area": "A" } },
    { "app": "rh", "action": "document:read",
      "resource": { "type": "document", "id": "d2", "attributes": { "area": "A" } },
      "subjectAttributes": { "area": "A" } }
  ]
}

### EXPECTED  200 OK
### {
###   "decisions": [
###     { "allowed": true,  "reason": "…assigned-access…", "policyVersion": "2", … },
###     { "allowed": false, "reason": "…default deny…",     "policyVersion": "2", … },
###     { "allowed": true,  "reason": "…area-scope…",       "policyVersion": "2", … }
###   ]
### }
### (decisions[i] corresponds to requests[i])


### B2) Batch across apps — each item is scoped to its own app (ADR-024)
POST {{host}}/v1/evaluate/batch
Authorization: {{auth}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "requests": [
    { "app": "rh",   "action": "document:read",
      "resource": { "type": "document", "id": "d1", "attributes": { "assignees": ["test-user"] } } },
    { "app": "nami", "action": "document:read",
      "resource": { "type": "document", "id": "d1", "attributes": { "assignees": ["test-user"] } } }
  ]
}

### EXPECTED  200 OK  →  decisions[0].allowed = true  (rh policy applies)
###                      decisions[1].allowed = false (rh policy invisible to nami)


### B3) 400 — an item without `app` fails the whole batch
POST {{host}}/v1/evaluate/batch
Authorization: {{auth}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "requests": [
    { "app": "rh", "action": "document:read",
      "resource": { "type": "document", "id": "d1" } },
    { "action": "document:read",
      "resource": { "type": "document", "id": "d2" } }
  ]
}

### EXPECTED  400  code: "BAD_REQUEST"  →  "app must not be blank."
### The whole batch fails; there is no partial result and no silent deny.


### ============================================================================
### C) GET /v1/permissions  — cacheable flat permission list for subject + ?app
### ============================================================================
### QUERY PARAMS:
###   app  (REQUIRED)  application context; 400 if missing/blank
### Subject is resolved from the JWT (self only; the delegated form is deferred to
### its own ADR).
###
### RESPONSE (PermissionsResponse):
###   { subject, app, permissions: [ "resource:verb", … ], policyVersion, evaluatedAt }
### Safe to cache per (subject + app + policyVersion); policyVersion changes when
### policies change → use it as a cache key / invalidation signal.
###
### NOTE: today `permissions` returns an empty list (option A); the bulk
### permission-listing mechanism is a separate future ADR. The CONTRACT below is
### stable even though the list is currently empty.

### C1) permissions for app "rh"
GET {{host}}/v1/permissions?app=rh
Authorization: {{auth}}

### EXPECTED  200 OK
### {
###   "subject": "<sub-from-jwt>",
###   "app": "rh",
###   "permissions": [],                 ← currently empty (option A); contract stable
###   "policyVersion": "2",
###   "evaluatedAt": "2026-07-13T…Z"
### }


### C2) 400 — missing 'app' query parameter
GET {{host}}/v1/permissions
Authorization: {{auth}}

### EXPECTED  400  (problem+json)  →  "'app' query parameter must not be blank."


### C3) 401 — no token (unauthenticated)
GET {{host}}/v1/permissions?app=rh

### EXPECTED  401  (OIDC challenge, no problem+json body)


### ============================================================================
### FIELD REFERENCE
### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
### EvaluationRequest { app*, action*, resource*, context?, subjectAttributes?, subject? }
###                     (* = required;  app added by ADR-024)
### ResourceRef       { type*, id?, attributes?: {…} }
### Decision          { allowed, reason, decisionId, policyVersion, obligations: [Obligation] }
### BatchEvaluationRequest { requests: [EvaluationRequest] }   ← every item needs app
### BatchEvaluationResult  { decisions: [Decision] }           ← same order as requests
### PermissionsResponse    { subject, app, permissions: [String], policyVersion, evaluatedAt }
###
### Attribute paths in conditions: subject.id | subject.attr.* | resource.type |
###   resource.id | resource.attr.* | context.*
###
### SCOPING (ADR-024): selection is (app, resourceType, verb). resourceType is a
### per-app namespace — two apps may both define "document" and never collide.
### ============================================================================
